sentences: Jane Monheit (born November 3, 1977) is an American jazz and pop vocalist.
She attended the Usdan Summer Camp for the Arts.
At the Manhattan School of Music she studied voice under Peter Eldridge; she graduated in 1999.
She was runner-up to Teri Thornton in the 1998 vocal competition at the Thelonious Monk Institute of Jazz, in Washington, DC.
When she was 22, she released her first album, Never Never Land (N-Coded, 2000).
Its first release was The Songbook Sessions (2016), an homage to Fitzgerald.
Monheit's vocals were featured in the 2010 film Never Let Me Go for the titular song, written by Luther Dixon, and credited to the fictional Judy Bridgewater.
